<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-207-100 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 430 516</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  March 3 1991 p5F(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Program brings clarity to chaos. (Autodesk Inc.'s James Gleick'sChaos: the Software simulation software) (Software Review)(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shannon, L.R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Autodesk Inc's $59.95 James Gleick's Chaos: the Softwaresimulation software is based on Gleick's 1986 book 'Chaos: Makinga New Science,' which deals with the development of chaos theory.andO;The package includes six programs dealing with Mandelbrot sets,magnets and pendulums, and strange attractors; the other threeprograms are called a chaos game, fractal forgeries and toyuniverses.andP;  The software ships with a 200-page manual, and cangenerate images for business presentations, video art and othergraphics needs.andP;  Chaos runs on IBM-compatible microcomputers andrequires 640Kbytes of memory, two floppy disk drives or one floppydrive and a hard drive, MS-DOS 2.0 or later and a color monitorusing an EGA or VGA graphics card.andP;  Recommended is a mathcoprocessor to handle the number calculations.andP;  The software comeson four 5.25-inch or two 3.5-inch disks.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Autodesk Inc. (Products).andO;Ticker:    ACAD.andO;Product:   James Gleick's Chaos: the software (Simulation software).andO;Topic:     SimulationSoftwareEvaluationScienceFractals.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>